<br>
That alone is reason for most, to not want to take the step up to leading, organizing, and executing a raid like this. It takes a lot of sweat and effort to organize a raid with this many people. It would be tough enough to do for a large guild, where everyone already is familiar with each other, each other's playing styles, the rules and plan of attack for the raid, and the familiarity of knowing everyone on the raid. Try to do the same thing on a CoG raid and it is that much more difficult: Lots of people on these raids have never even met a majority of the other fellow raiders, all come from different guilds with different styles of gameplay, some are not guilded at all, some are disciplined and experienced and listen and follow instructions while others don't or won't. And some people come to these raids with extensive solo careers under their belts, so they are not as finely tuned for depending on others, or for following orders, and such.<br>
<br>
The fact is, the diversity of people, and their styles makes these raids even tougher to do, than say a one guild raid with the same objective. They can still be done, even with the diversity of people and styles, it's just that it is a lot harder.<br>
<br>
I gladdens me to see people getting up there against the odds, to lead these events. I saddens me to see personal attacks on the leadership, and not just objective critisism of points on the raid, with suggestions of ways to improve upon things.<br>
<br>
If anyone else would like to take a leadership position, it is a matter of volunteering, and organizing a raid. With the number of qualified and experienced people in CoG, there should certainly be more people offering to lead these events to share the responsibility in making these things take place. <br>
<br>
It takes a lot to get up and do these. I am not confident I could lead one. I depend on others to do that. I have volunteered to help organize and be backing support for others who have led them in the past. I wish to encourage you both to not get discouraged. A raid that goes horribly wrong, yet you learn from, is not a failure. Only the objective was not met. You will improve upon things with each successive raid. <br>
<br>
I also challenge anyone who thinks they can do it better to bring it on. Not as in a challenge to see who leads better, but as a means for sharing the duties and burdens of making these things happen, so it's not only a couple of people doing it all the time for everyone elses benefit.<br>
<br>
I admire your efforts, Flarren and Lagdalen. You have won my respect as leaders. I wish you all the best in you future raids. Thank you for providing raids that this many people can go on that otherwise would not get to. <br>
<br>
